<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="66">
<taxonomicName LSID="FFCCBAA2-E87E-62C4-10CE-47496AD1EEF3" authority="Vell., Fl. Flumin.: 31. 1829." authorityName="Vell., Fl. Flumin.: 31. 1829." class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Commelina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Commelina singularis" order="Commelinales" pageId="7" pageNumber="66" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="singularis">Commelina singularis Vell., Fl. Flumin.: 31. 1829.</taxonomicName>
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Commelina singularis Vell. A-B Original plate of Vellozo's C. singularis: A line drawings of habit, inflorescence and floral characters B detail of floral characters. C, photos of a natural population of Tripogandra diuretica from the Jardim Botanico Rio de Janeiro, RJ: detail of the inflorescence, showing flowers with white corolla D-E photos of T. diuretica from the municipality of Petropolis, RJ: D detail of floral characters of a flower with lilac corolla E detail showing the leaves (note the parallel venation characteristic of the species) SS sterile stamens; FS fertile stamens; Gy gynoecium. Photo of C. singularis plate from Biodiversity Heritage Library; All field photos by M. O. O. Pellegrini." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.78.11932.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/130208" pageId="7" pageNumber="66">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="67" type="lectotype">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="67">
<pageBreakToken pageId="8" pageNumber="67" start="start">Lectotype</pageBreakToken>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="67">
(designated here). [illustration] Original parchment plate of Flora fluminensis in the Manuscript Section of the Biblioteca Nacional do Rio de Janeiro [mss1095062_080] and later published in Vellozo, Fl. flumin. Icon. 1: t. 76, pro parte, flowers and inflorescence only. Epitype (designated here). BRAZIL. Rio de Janeiro: Rio de Janeiro, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Área">Area</normalizedToken>
do Jardim 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Botânico">Botanico</normalizedToken>
do Rio de Janeiro, fl., fr., 21 Dec 1995, J.A. Lira Neto 194 (RB 2ex, barcode RB00685321!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="67" type="accepted name">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="67">Accepted name.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="67">
<taxonomicName class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Tripogandra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tripogandra diuretica" order="Commelinales" pageId="8" pageNumber="67" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="diuretica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="67">Tripogandra diuretica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Mart.) Handlos.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="68" type="taxonomical notes">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="68">
<pageBreakToken pageId="9" pageNumber="68" start="start">Taxonomical</pageBreakToken>
notes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="68">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vellozo’s">Vellozo's</normalizedToken>
plate for 
<taxonomicName family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. singularis" order="Commelinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">C. singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(1831: t. 76) shows a creeping plant with eudicot-like leaves (net-veined and a single apparently trifoliate leaf), not identifiable as any known species of 
<taxonomicName family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Commelinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="family">Commelinaceae</taxonomicName>
. Nevertheless, the inflorescence type (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Commelina singularis Vell. A-B Original plate of Vellozo's C. singularis: A line drawings of habit, inflorescence and floral characters B detail of floral characters. C, photos of a natural population of Tripogandra diuretica from the Jardim Botanico Rio de Janeiro, RJ: detail of the inflorescence, showing flowers with white corolla D-E photos of T. diuretica from the municipality of Petropolis, RJ: D detail of floral characters of a flower with lilac corolla E detail showing the leaves (note the parallel venation characteristic of the species) SS sterile stamens; FS fertile stamens; Gy gynoecium. Photo of C. singularis plate from Biodiversity Heritage Library; All field photos by M. O. O. Pellegrini." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.78.11932.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/130208" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">6A, C</figureCitation>
), details of the androecium (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Commelina singularis Vell. A-B Original plate of Vellozo's C. singularis: A line drawings of habit, inflorescence and floral characters B detail of floral characters. C, photos of a natural population of Tripogandra diuretica from the Jardim Botanico Rio de Janeiro, RJ: detail of the inflorescence, showing flowers with white corolla D-E photos of T. diuretica from the municipality of Petropolis, RJ: D detail of floral characters of a flower with lilac corolla E detail showing the leaves (note the parallel venation characteristic of the species) SS sterile stamens; FS fertile stamens; Gy gynoecium. Photo of C. singularis plate from Biodiversity Heritage Library; All field photos by M. O. O. Pellegrini." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.78.11932.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/130208" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">6B, D</figureCitation>
), and the morphological description of six dimorphic stamens, three of which are staminodial - &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Stamina sex, quorum tria nectaria mentiuntur</emphasis>
&quot; - (
<bibRefCitation author="Vellozo, JMC (1825)" journalOrPublisher="Typographia Nationali, Rio de Janeiro" pageId="12" pageNumber="71" refId="B35" refString="Vellozo, JMC (1825), 1829. Florae fluminensis. Typographia Nationali, Rio de Janeiro" title="Florae fluminensis." year="1829">Vellozo 1829</bibRefCitation>
), consistently allows this name to be associated to the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Tripogandra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tripogandra" order="Commelinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Tripogandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Raf. Another remarkable feature of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Vellozo’s">Vellozo's</normalizedToken>
plate is the gynoecium, which is illustrated with a very short and slightly curved style (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Commelina singularis Vell. A-B Original plate of Vellozo's C. singularis: A line drawings of habit, inflorescence and floral characters B detail of floral characters. C, photos of a natural population of Tripogandra diuretica from the Jardim Botanico Rio de Janeiro, RJ: detail of the inflorescence, showing flowers with white corolla D-E photos of T. diuretica from the municipality of Petropolis, RJ: D detail of floral characters of a flower with lilac corolla E detail showing the leaves (note the parallel venation characteristic of the species) SS sterile stamens; FS fertile stamens; Gy gynoecium. Photo of C. singularis plate from Biodiversity Heritage Library; All field photos by M. O. O. Pellegrini." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.78.11932.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/130208" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">6B</figureCitation>
). This feature distances 
<taxonomicName family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. singulars" order="Commelinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="singulars">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">C. singulars</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="Commelina" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Commelina" order="Commelinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Commelina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
where the style is long and sigmoid, bringing it closer to 
<taxonomicName class="Monocotyledoneae" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Tripogandra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Tripogandra" order="Commelinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Tripogandra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The leaves illustrated by Vellozo belong to the genus 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Polygonum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Polygonum" order="Polygonales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Polygonum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Polygonum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Polygonales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Polygonaceae</taxonomicName>
), which usually possesses white to pink to lilac flowers, and occurs in the same marshes as 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. diuretica" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="diuretica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">T. diuretica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This confusion is apparently common in Brazilian herbaria, where 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Polygonaceae" genus="Polygonum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Polygonum" order="Polygonales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Polygonum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens are commonly misidentified as commelinaceous taxa (Pellegrini pers. obs.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="68">
<bibRefCitation author="Vellozo, JMC (1825)" journalOrPublisher="Typographia Nationali, Rio de Janeiro" pageId="12" pageNumber="71" refId="B35" refString="Vellozo, JMC (1825), 1829. Florae fluminensis. Typographia Nationali, Rio de Janeiro" title="Florae fluminensis." year="1829">Vellozo (1829</bibRefCitation>
: 31) also mentions that 
<taxonomicName family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. singularis" order="Commelinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">C. singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found growing in slow-water environments - &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Aquis stagnantibus, et confluentibus habitat</emphasis>
&quot; -. Only 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. diuretica" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="diuretica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">T. diuretica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. warmingiana" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="warmingiana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">T. warmingiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Seub.) Handlos occur in the state of Rio de Janeiro; the first being very common, extremely variable in size and flower morphology, and normally occurring in marshy areas; the second being very rare, uniformly small in size and flower morphology, and occurring in drier areas (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.91.2.2" author="Pellegrini, MOO" journalOrPublisher="Phytotaxa" pageId="12" pageNumber="71" pagination="39 - 49" refId="B25" refString="Pellegrini, MOO, Aona-Pinheiro, LYS, Forzza, RC, 2013. Taxonomy and conservation status of Tripogandra warmingiana (Seub.) Handlos (Commelinaceae), a previously obscure taxon from Brazil. Phytotaxa 91 (2): 39 - 49, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.91.2.2" title="Taxonomy and conservation status of Tripogandra warmingiana (Seub.) Handlos (Commelinaceae), a previously obscure taxon from Brazil." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/phytotaxa.91.2.2" volume="91" year="2013">Pellegrini et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Thus, 
<taxonomicName family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. singularis" order="Commelinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">C. singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here regarded as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName genus="T." lsidName="T. diuretica" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="diuretica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">T. diuretica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In accordance to the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">Code</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="McNeill, J" journalOrPublisher="International Journal of Botany" pageId="12" pageNumber="71" refId="B21" refString="McNeill, J, Barrie, FR, Buck, WR, Demoulin, V, Greuter, W, Hawksworth, DL, Herendeen, PS, Knapp, S, Marhold, K, Prado, J, Prud'Homme Van Reine, WF, Smith, GF, Wiersema, JH, Turland, NJ, 2012. (2012) International Code of Botanical Nomenclature (Melbourne Code). Adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Regnum Vegetabile 154. A.R.G. Gantner Verlag KG, 1-240." title="(2012) International Code of Botanical Nomenclature (Melbourne Code). Adopted by the Eighteenth International Botanical Congress Melbourne, Australia, July 2011. Regnum Vegetabile 154. A. R. G. Gantner Verlag KG, 1 - 240." year="2012">McNeill et al., 2012</bibRefCitation>
, Art. 9.8), in order to avoid future confusions and to fix the application of this name, we herein designate an epitype for 
<taxonomicName family="Commelinaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. singularis" order="Commelinales" pageId="9" pageNumber="68" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="68">C. singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
